doc.title: AccoTest (688200.SS): OSAT Capex cycle recovery and product migration to drive growth ahead; PP up to Amb245; Buy
doc.source_uri: 2025-09-02/AccoTest (688200.SS)_ OSAT Capex cycle recovery and product migration to drive growth ahead; TP up to Rmb245; Buy_2025-09-02

passages.text: Accotest reported 2Q25 net income b our/BBG consensus by \(29\% /20\%\) reflecting OSAT capex recovery and Accotest's product lines expansion. Management is positive on order and revenues growth momentum in 2H25, supported by capex cycle recovery, overseas market growth, and product expansion to address demand from data center/ automotive market, affirming our constructive view on Accotest. We are positive on company's comprehensive offerings from analog/ mixed signal testers to high- end digital/ SoC testers, meanwhile expanding to in- house ASIC for testing system (Report link). Maintain Buy with a 12m TP up to Rmb245. For more, read our ChipActs 3 report.

Positive on 2H25 ahead: Management is positive on order momentum and sequential revenues growth in 2H25E, driven by (1) OSAT capacity in expansion, riding on China Semis capex expansion and moves to local OSAT suppliers with migration toward advanced packaging; (2) overseas business ramp up across Malaysia, India etc., and the company has built facilities in Malaysia to support local delivery and services; and (3) products expansion across STS8300 (mixed signals tester), STS8600 (digital tester), and upgraded STS8200 AXE- Plus for SiC/GaN modules testing, driven by rising demand on data center power supply with better efficiency.

2Q25 Rev/ NI beat: The company's NI in 2Q25 was \(29\% /20\%\) ahead of our estimates and BBG consensus, supported by stronger- than- expected revenues growth, better GM on mix upgrade and improving efficiency. The 2Q25 revenues were \(19\% /13\%\) higher than our estimates and BBG consensus, reflecting OSAT capex recovery, accelerated growth of overseas business, and new products ramp up. 2Q GM was up to \(72.5\%\) (vs. 1Q at \(71.3\%\) ) on favorable product mix.
Exhibit 1:AccoTest 2025 result snapshot
Source: Company data, Bloomberg, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Earnings revisions: We factor in Accotest 2Q25 result and raise our net income estimates by \(6\% /9\% /9\%\) in 2025/26/27E on higher revenues, higher GM and lower Opex ratio. We revise up revenues in 2025- 27E on higher shipment of testers, supported by capex cycle recovery and new products ramp up. We revise up GM by 0.8ppts/0.9ppts/0.9ppts in 2025- 27E to reflect product mix changes towards testers carrying higher margin. We revise down Opex ratio by 1.3ppts/1.5ppts in 2026/27E on larger revenues scale and improving manufacturing efficiency.

GS vs. Bloomberg consensus: Our NI is \(9\% /22\%\) higher than Bloomberg consensus in- 2025/26E, mainly due to higher revenues and lower Opex ratio in 2026E. The higher revenues reflect our positive view on Accotest as local semiconductor equipment leader to benefit from OSAT capacity expansion and company's product expansion to mixed- signal and digital testers. The lower Opex ratio is supported by company's improving manufacturing efficiency, while the company maintains high R&D spending on new product development.
Exhibit 5:GS vs.Bloomberg consensus
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research, Bloomberg

Valuation: We derive our TP by near- term 2026E P/E (methodology unchanged). Our target P/E multiple of 45x (vs. previously 38x) derived from peers 2026E PE vs. 2026- 27E NI YoY (methodology unchanged with updated number). Our target PE multiple raised from 38x to 45x given higher 2026- 27E NI YoY (34% vs. 32% previously) and market re- rating on SPE under China Semis rising capex. The new target P/E multiple of 45x is line with company's avg. P/E at 48x and within the company's historical trading range since 2020. As a result, our TP is raised to Rmb245 (vs. previously at Rmb189). Maintain Buy.
Exhibit 6: Target P/E multiple is derived from local/global peers' 2026 P/E and 26-27E avg. net income growth

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
